76561198042010476,Not Recommended,212160,29429726,Posted: 22 January,all,Rzaney,"As much as I'd to give this game a thumbs up, the game has several issues that have been brought up time and time again and never been fixed simply because Nexon NA doesn't care. I have at least 1000 hours overall put into this game, some on the launcher and some on steam, but I'm thinking of stopping entirely now due to some recent events that have taken place. (Jan 22, 2017, tl;dr for the game itself at the bottom)But for starters, we'll talk about the game itself- The good:- The combat system is simply one of the best, if not the best in any MMO, and even better than some single player oriented games I've played like Dark Souls and The Witcher. The hitboxes are clean, the action is quick (and even faster once you get some attack speed), and the bosses have a lot of variety in the mid to late game that keeps you on your toes, and stumbles even some of the best players from time to time. The hack and slash elements here are very well done. I would entirely recommend someone to play this game simply for the combat system(but to be aware the early game is very muchly a grind and a faceroll until about the ainle missions, or even the polar bear if you're new to this type of game).- The character classes are very diverse and unique from one another. Nearly every single character plays entirely different to the other characters, even between their weapon types if they utilize more than one. You want safer, consistent ranged combat, you pick your xgun or bow Kai. You want to get off a huge burst of spells and gtfo, you pick your staff Evie. You want to get in the face of the boss all the time, and stay there. you pick your Pillar or Cestus Karok, or Greatsword Hurk. You want to play reactively, you pick Twin Sword Vella dancing with ease at the bosses attack patterns, or a sturdy shield maiden in Fiona. And there's still others who fall on both ends of the spectrum. Find the character you like, and stick with them till 40 to see if you like the game(follow AP guides early on so you don't get screwed later).- The character customization is also amazing. The armor sets can be mixed and matched however you want for the most part(be aware of set bonuses). There's an entire outfitter shop with all sorts of different hairstyles, tattoos, inner armors, etc. The bad part is that most of it costs a LOT of money. I'm talking $5 for a single head, armor, leg, glove, or boot customization, but for overall variety, and in such an old game engine, it certainly is vast and very customizable down to some of the colors of the armor pieces themselves.*-------------------------------------------------------------*- The bad:- The game is pretty much entirely peer to peer hosted, so whoever's the host needs good internet or no one can play properly. While not usually a problem with the earlier missions that only accompany up to 4 people, it gets a bit hairier with the 6 or 8 man raids, or when huge masses of mobs start spawning in and the host's computer can't keep up. On the flipside, it does allow people to play on other servers with friends if they live nearby with relatively low ping and consistency, so that's nice.- The game is VERY much a cash grab at this point. The only thing keeping it afloat are the whales, but most of them only stay simply because of the time invested through sunk cost fallacy. In a free to play game, the community needs to be alive enough for the game to be commercially successful, but eventually even the whales will quit eventually. It's been very sad seeing the community slowly dwindle over the years and now hardly seeing anyone in even the first 10 channels.- The game is poorly optimized. It's built off a very old engine from more than a decade ago, and rarely, if ever, reaches 60fps for even the best gaming rigs. Sure it looks pretty on higher settings, but the game is all about functionality. This can be improved by turning off UI elements(the buff indicators and their tooltips in particular are resource heavey due to their updating every single second, if you want better functionality for this game I'd recommend turning off any UI elements you deem unnecessary for the fight itself.) but will still have a few issues occasionally.- Progression in the game can be heavily RNG based. For earlier levels it doesn't matter that much for what weapons and other things you use as long as they're appropriately leveled. If you're an experienced player you can easily get to the late game within 20 hours of gameplay, especially when you know when to upgrade things, or just the weapon, etc, and how to play the game itself effectively. For new players, however, it can be very confusing and grindy when they try to farm for things they could just buy on the market for dirt cheap that's the correct level for progressing through the game. This is also a problem with the enhancing and enchanting systems in the game which can be seen here:http://vindictus.gamepedia.com/Item_Enhancementhttp://vindictus.gamepedia.com/Enchanting.This can make it hard to progress in the game after a certain threshold where it's required to be useful in any way during raids or other battles.- Nexon NA's support is ABYSMAL. The community mods are mostly just people ruling with an iron fist over anything that goes against their own preconceived biases, and Nexon has issues with fan made sites outside of their own forums or wiki. Dealing with the support team is mostly just rehashed, premade messages that get you nowhere.*-------------------------------------------------------------*The recent issue:The problem I have is with the built in security feature BlackCipher, which poorly summarized, works by testing the amount of RAM usage during your gameplay to detect abnormalities in gameplay to test for bots, and automatically adds ""points"". Once you reach a threshold you get auto banned. This also runs in the background and causes significant stuttering and lag for the actual game itself. The prime reason why I'm quitting now is because recently one of the most prominent community members, Sanitee, was banned due to his personally developed, and widely helpful Vindictus Inn site and database being marked as being a ""hack"" of sorts due to BlackCipher. This resulted in a permanent ban that he's tried to get uplifted to no avail, and which Nexon NA(or at least the minuscule amount of actual workers there) claims cannot be undone. In response, Shippuu(who's review can be seen nearby as well) has closed the other prominent fan site Vindictus Manual in retaliation and replaced it with a heartfelt message instead. These two key figures were widely regarded as some of the most helpful and experienced players, as well as prominent game developers devoting days of their time to making functioning websites for the entire community, and Nexon showed their true colors on how much they ""care"" regarding the issue, and the game itself. Because of this, I can't play this game in good conscience and refuse to spend more time playing a game that the developers(or at least Nexon rather than Devcat for the most part) care nothing about and which will die because of negligence. You might just get banned for no other reason than you forgot you overclocked your PC earlier out of nowhere, which is not okay in any online game. Nexon has entirely sweeped the incident under the rug out of sight of everything else as well.Overall, I'd say to try it until like level 40ish with whatever character you feel most comfortable with and see if you like it(better with friends), but understand that Nexon doesn't care even a little about anything, and you might be screwed later on down the line for no reason whatsoever, and many prominent people are leaving because of Nexon's negligence and disinterest.tl;dr : Gameplay++++, Customization+, Character Variety++Peer 2 Peer mostly--, Optimization--, Cash Grab--, RNG--, Nexon----------"
